{
  "questionId": "gfg-sub-aptitude-number-series-solved-questions-and-answers",
  "title": "Number Series - Solved Questions and Answers",
  "content": {
    "problemStatement": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>A\u00a0</span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/aptitude/number-series-in-quantitative-aptitude/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><b><strong>number series</strong></b></a><span>\u00a0is an ordered sequence of numbers following a specific pattern or rule. These patterns can involve addition, multiplication, or more complex mathematical relationships. Number series are used to develop logical thinking and appear in math problems, puzzles, and aptitude tests.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Number Series questions and answers are provided below for you to learn and practice.</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Question 1: </strong></b><span>Find what number would come in place of the question mark(?).</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>2, 5, 12.5, ?, 78.125, 195.3125</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 31.25</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 40.25</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 32.50</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a021.00</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:\u00a0</strong></b><span> (a) 31.25</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b><span>\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>If you observe the pattern, then you can see\u00a0</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>\u00a02 \u00d7 2.5 = 5</span><br/><span>5 \u00d7 2.5 = 12.5</span><br/><span>12.5 \u00d7 2.5 = 31.25</span><br/><span>31.25 \u00d7 2.5 = \u00a078.125</span><br/><span>78.125 \u00d7 2.5 = 195.3125</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the correct answer is \u00a031.25</span><br/><span>\u00a0</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 2: </strong></b><span>Find what number would come in place of the question mark(?).</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>50, 45, 40, 35, 30, ?\u00a0</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 28</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 15</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 25</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a020</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: \u00a0</strong></b><span>(c) 25</span><b><strong>\u00a0</strong></b></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b><span>\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>\u00a0If you observe the pattern, then you will see, it's nothing but constant difference series.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>50 - 5 = 45</span><br/><span>45 - 5 = 40</span><br/><span>40 - 5 = 35</span><br/><span>35 - 5 = 30</span><br/><span>30 - 5 = 25</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the correct answer is</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>25.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 3:</strong></b><span> Find what number would come in place of the question mark(?).</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>-10, -8, 6, 40, 102, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 105</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 200</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 216</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0129</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(b) 200</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing patterns carefully you will find that this question belongs to the category of square series.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-10 + ( 2</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>- 2 ) = -8</span><br/><span>-8 + ( 4</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>- 2 ) = 6</span><br/><span>6 + ( 6</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>- 2 ) = 40</span><br/><span>40 + \u00a0( 8</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>- 2 ) = 102</span><br/><span>102 + \u00a0( 10</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>- 2 ) = \u00a0200</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the correct answer is 200.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 4:</strong></b><span> Find what number would come in place of the question mark(?).</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>25, 49, 121, 169, ?\u00a0</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 225</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 256</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 289</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0361</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(c) 289</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing patterns carefully, you will observe that, this series is based on two concepts one is squares and the other is a prime number.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 25</span><br/><span>7</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 49</span><br/><span>11</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>= 121</span><br/><span>13</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 169</span><br/><span>17</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 289</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the correct answer is 289</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 5:</strong></b><span> Find what number would come in place of the question mark(?).</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>1, 30, 5, 26, 9, 22, 13, 18, ? \u00a0</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 17</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 22</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 28</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a019</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(a) \u00a017\u00a0</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing the pattern carefully, you will observe that, this series consist of 2 different series.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Let me point out them for ease of understanding ---</span><br/><span>1 + 4 = 5</span><br/><span>5 + 4 = 9</span><br/><span>9 + 4 \u00a0= 13</span><br/><span>13+4= 17.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Similarly,</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>30 - 4 \u00a0= 26</span><br/><span>26 - 4 = 22</span><br/><span>22 - 4 =18</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 6:</strong></b><span> Find the number that will come in the place of the question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 4, 18, ?, 100, 180, 294, 448</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 62</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 86</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 38</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a048</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(d) \u00a048</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b><br/><span>Observing pattern carefully you will find that this question belongs to the category of squares and cube series.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 2</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 8 \u2013 4 = 4</span><br/><span>3</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 27 \u2013 9 = 18</span><br/><span>4</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 4</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 64 \u2013 16 =</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>48</span><br/><span>5</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 125 \u2013 25 = 100</span><br/><span>6</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 6</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 216 \u2013 36 = 180</span><br/><span>7</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 7</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 343 \u2013 49 = 294</span><br/><span>8</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> \u2013 8</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 512 \u2013 64 = 448</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence 48 would be our answer, as it is the number that would come in place of a question mark.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 7:</strong></b><span> Find the number that will come in the place of the question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 11, 12, 15, 20, 27, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 36</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 35</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 38</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a041</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(a) 36</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Here, the series follows a pattern of the sum of consecutive odd numbers.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>11 + 1 = 12</span><br/><span>12 + 3 = 15</span><br/><span>15 + 5 = 20</span><br/><span>20 + 7 = 27</span><br/><span>27 + 9 = 36.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the missing number would be 36.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 8: </strong></b><span>Find the number that will come in the place of the question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>14, 25, 47, 91, 179, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 255</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 321</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 355</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) 211</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:  </strong></b><span>(c) 355</span><b><strong>\u00a0</strong></b></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>\u00a0</strong></b><span>observing the pattern we get that the difference between consecutive terms is being doubled every time.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>25 \u2013 14 = 11</span><br/><span>47 \u2013 25 = 22</span><br/><span>91 \u2013 47 = 44</span><br/><span>179 \u2013 91 = 88</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>So, if 88 is doubled, we get 176.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, 179 + 176 = 355</span><br/><span>Hence the missing term is</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>355.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 9: </strong></b><span>Find the number that will come in the place of the question mark. </span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>4, 6, 9, 14, 21, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 28</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 32</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 34</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) 40</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(b) 32\u00a0</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing the pattern, one can easily come to know that, the</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>difference between consecutive terms is a prime number.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>4 + 2 = 6</span><br/><span>6 + 3 = 9</span><br/><span>9 + 5 = 14</span><br/><span>14 + 7 = 21</span><br/><span>21 + 11 = 32.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, the missing number will be \u00a032.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 10: </strong></b><span>Find the number which would come in place of question marks.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 3, 4, 7, 8, 11, 12, \u00a0?, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 13, 14</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 18, 20</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 15, 16</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a019, 20</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(c) 15, 16</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>\u00a0This is a Hybrid series, \u00a0which is formed from the combination of two series i.e 3,7,11,.... and 4,8, 12.</span><br/><span>So, the difference between every term in different series is 4. hence 11 + 4 would be the next term i.e 15 \u00a0</span><br/><span>and 12 + 4 =16 is the further next term.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 11:</strong></b><span> Find the number which is wrong.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong>2, 3, 12, 37, 86, 166, 288</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 2</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 12</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 37</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0166 </span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(d) 166</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing the pattern carefully, every term is formed from a sum of (the previous term and consecutive odd number squares).</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2 + 1</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 2 + 1 = 3</span><br/><span>3 + 3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 3 + 9 = 12</span><br/><span>12 + 5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 12 + 25 = 37</span><br/><span>37 + 7</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> \u00a0= 37 + 49 = 86</span><br/><span>86 + 9</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 86 + 81 = 167</span><br/><span>167 + 11</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 167 + 121 = 288.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Clearly, we can see that 167 should be there instead of 166. Hence</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>166</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>is the wrong term.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 12:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series: </span><b><strong> 81 : 101 :: 121 : ? </strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 141</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 143</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 170</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0145</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(d) 145 \u00a0</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Here 81 is nothing but 9</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>\u00a0and 101 is nothing but (9 + 1)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> +1</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>So, likewise this</span><br/><span>121 is nothing but 11</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><br/><span>so ,next term will be (11 + 1)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 1 = 145</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 13:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 11 : 121 :: 15 : ?\u00a0</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 169</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 196</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 225</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0256 </span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b><span> (c) 225</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation: \u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing pattern we get,\u00a0</span><br/><span>Here, 11</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 121</span><br/><span>So, 15</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>= 225</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>So, the missing number is 225.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 14: </strong></b><span>Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 2, 4, 8, 10, 14, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 16</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 18</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 24</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a020</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b><span> (a) 16</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b><span>\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This series is an alternating series, where a pattern following is +2, +4, +2, +4, and so on\u00a0</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2 + 2 = 4</span><br/><span>4 + 4 = 8\u00a0</span><br/><span>8 + 2 = 10</span><br/><span>10 + 4 = 14</span><br/><span>14 + 2 = 16\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence the next term will be 16.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 15: </strong></b><span>Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:  </span><b><strong>1, 8, 9, 64, \u00a0?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 27</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 49</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 25</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a064</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(c) \u00a025</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Observing carefully one can come to know that this series is nothing but squares and cubes of numbers starting from 1\u00a0</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>1</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 1</span><br/><span>2</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> = 8</span><br/><span>3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = \u00a09</span><br/><span>4</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span> = \u00a064</span><br/><span>5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = \u00a025\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, 25 will be the answer.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 16:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:\u00a0</span><b><strong>6, 11, 18, 27, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 33</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 40</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 38</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a081</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: \u00a0</strong></b><span>(c) \u00a038</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:</strong></b><span>\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Here, every term is squares from (starting from 2 ) with the addition of 2.\u00a0</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 2 = 6</span><br/><span>3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 2 =11</span><br/><span>4</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 2 = 18</span><br/><span>5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 2 = 27</span><br/><span>6</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + 2 = 38\u00a0</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 17: </strong></b><span>Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 3, 4.5, 9, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 22.5</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 18</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 13.5</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) 27 </span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: \u00a0</strong></b><span>(a) \u00a022.5\u00a0</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation: \u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This series is a product based, below is the pattern for finding the next term\u00a0</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>3 \u00d7 1 = 3</span><br/><span>3 \u00a0\u00d7 1.5 = 4.5\u00a0</span><br/><span>4.5 \u00a0\u00d7 \u00a02 = 9</span><br/><span>9 \u00a0\u00d7 \u00a02.5 = \u00a022.5\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, 22.5 will be our answer.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 18:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, ?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 13</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 17</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 19</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a012</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b><span>(a) 13</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>It can be seen in 2 ways,\u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>1. </strong></b><span>it is simple just a difference of 2 in every consecutive term that is --</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>3 + 2 = 5</span><br/><span>5 + 2 = 7</span><br/><span>7 + 2 = 9</span><br/><span>9 + 2 = 11</span><br/><span>11 + 2 =</span><b><strong> </strong></b><span>13. Hence 13 will be the answer.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2. It can also be seen as a difference of squares of numbers -</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>2</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 1</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 3</span><br/><span>3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 2</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 5</span><br/><span>4</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 3</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 7</span><br/><span>5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 4</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 9</span><br/><span>6</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 5</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = 11 \u00a0\u00a0</span><br/><span>7</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> - 6</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> = </span><b><strong>1</strong></b><span>3. Hence 13, will be the answer.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 19:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:</span><b><strong> 1, 7, 37, 187, 937, \u00a0?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 4687</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 1823</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 5687</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a05000</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b><span> (a) 4687 \u00a0</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation:\u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Here, every term is multiplied by 5, and adding 2 to get the next term of the series.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>1 \u00d7 5 + 2 = 7</span><br/><span>7 \u00d7 \u00a05 + 2 = 37</span><br/><span>37 \u00d7 5 + 2 = 187</span><br/><span>187 \u00d7 5 + 2 = 937</span><br/><span>937 \u00d7 5 + 2 = 4687</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, 4867 will be our answer.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Question 20:</strong></b><span> Find the number which would come in place of question mark.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Series:\u00a0</span><b><strong>1, 5, 19, 81, \u00a0?</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>a) 405</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>b) 411</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>c) 400</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>d) \u00a0395</span></p><pre><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b><span> (b) 411</span></pre><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>Explanation: \u00a0</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><strong>\u00a0</strong></b><span> Below is the pattern to crack this series</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>1 \u00d7 2 + 3 = 5</span><br/><span>5 \u00d7 3 + 4 = 19</span><br/><span>19 \u00d7 4 + 5 = 81\u00a0</span><br/><span>81 \u00d7 5 + 6 = 411 \u00a0</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Hence, 411 will be our answer.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=\"also-check\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Also Check:</span></h3><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>\u27a3 Test your knowledge-\u00a0</span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/quizzes/series-gq/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Quiz</span></a><span>!</span></p></blockquote>",
